<br>
I have never ran a Naggy raid, and only been on one.. but killed a few other dragons, so going by them. <br>
1. Have someone aggro Naggy and run out the door (This will cause Naggy to run around his lair going nuts)<br>
2. Have everyone up the first set of stairs from the pit waiting for engage. <br>
3. Main tank runs up the 2nd set of steps and sits at naggy's door waiting for Naggy to make the lap to the door. <br>
4. When Naggy is inc, he engages and starts getting healed. (Key is to keep him alive)<br>
5. After 3-4 seconds have the rest of the raid charge, but keep him at the door.<br>
<br>
 Why door?  AE does not go around walls inside, so when you have 2 healers per group, they only have to heal 4 people instead of 6 (themselves) Almost doubling your chance to win.   It also allows wizzies to hide, wait for AE, run around corner, nuke, and hide again. Sometimes never getting hit by AE. <br>
<br>
 To speed up buffs, get rid of those Shammie buffs, except the HP ones.  Tanks should only get Focus (or altuna?), and STA from SHammies, the rest are just fluff and make buffing longer and more confusing. If Shammie is bored, he can toss the fluff buffs on the first 2 tanks, but no need to get all melee with that.<br>
<br>
 Buffing everything else is really hard to get right on Naggy raids as far as time goes. Hell, guilds who raid together all the time will always have issues with buffing, so I cant' really help ya there except just say, form groups, then buff. Group buffs with /target make it much easier.  Small tips:<br>
1. Have buffers /shout send me /tell for xxx buff - Melee (or caster) only. <br>
2. When buffers start getting lom, make sure necros and mages are feeding them. <br>
3. For group buffs (circles), make sure only group leaders send druids /tells for them.  Nothing, I mean *nothing* is more annoying to a buffer to get a /tell for a group buff from 2 different people in the same group. <br>
<br>
